      <emphasis effect="bold">Discussion</emphasis>
    </para>
    <para id="import-auto-id2017158">Units of radians are dimensionless and appear  in any relationship between angular and linear quantities.</para></example>
    <para id="import-auto-id1117830">So far, we have defined three rotational quantities— <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mi>, </m:mi><m:mi>ω</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{θ,ω} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{α} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. These quantities are analogous to the translational quantities <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mi>, </m:mi><m:mi>v</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{x,v} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, and <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>a</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{a} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. <link target-id="import-auto-id1572984"/> displays rotational quantities, the analogous translational quantities, and the relationships between them.</para>


